:"1247","1225":"1225","1235":"1235","1200":"1200","1155":"1155","about 1155":"about 1155","Tasley,Shropshire,England":"Tasley, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Wattlesborough, Shropshire, England":"Wattlesborough, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Tasley, Shropshire, England":"Tasley, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Corbet","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Corbett  .","History: Walter Corbet, a royal knight in 12th-century Scotland, was the first of that name in that kingdom. His 13th-century descendants were major landholders in the Borders, and in the 14th century they acquired lands in the North of Scotland."],"variants":[{"name":"Corbett","meanings":["English (West Midlands, of Norman origin): nickname from Old French <i>corbet</i> ‘raven’, probably denoting someone with dark hair or a dark complexion.","History: This is the name of a family descended from Hugh <i>Corbet</i>, a Norman baron who settled in Shropshire following the Norman Conquest. One of his descendants, Sir Richard Corbet, was granted land near Shrewsbury in 1223; since the 13th century, this place has been known as Moreton Corbet. The name was taken from Shropshire to Scotland in the 12th century and to northern Ireland in the 17th century, and thence to North America by at least one group of bearers of the name."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Roger Corbet ,Lord of Tasley was born about 1155, in Tasley, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Thomas Corbet, was 37 and his mother, Mrs Thomas Corbet, was 17. He married Cecily Hadley about 1212, in Shropshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 5 sons. He died before 1204, in his hometown."},"et":{"about 1155–bef 1204":"umbes 1155–enne 1204","1155–1204":"1155–1204","1174–1225":"1174–1225","1098–Male":"1098–Surnud","1173–1235":"1173–1235","1180–1247":"1180–1247","1200–1247":"1200–1247","1203–Male":"1203–Surnud","1120–Male":"1120–Surnud","1140–Female":"1140–Surnud","before 1155":"enne 1155","1120":"1120","1098":"1098","1174":"1174","1140":"1140","1173":"1173","1200 (of age 21 1221)":"1200","1180":"1180","Abt 1173":"umbes 1173","bef 1204":"enne 1204","1204":"1204","1203":"1203","1247":"1247","1225":"1225","1235":"1235","1200":"1200","1155":"1155","about 1155":"umbes 1155","Tasley,Shropshire,England":"Tasley, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Wattlesborough, Shropshire, England":"Wattlesborough, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Tasley, Shropshire, England":"Tasley, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1155–bef 1204":"noin 1155–ennen vuotta 1204","1155–1204":"1155–1204","1174–1225":"1174–1225","1098–Male":"1098–Kuollut","1173–1235":"1173–1235","1180–1247":"1180–1247","1200–1247":"1200–1247","1203–Male":"1203–Kuollut","1120–Male":"1120–Kuollut","1140–Female":"1140–Kuollut","before 1155":"ennen vuotta 1155","1120":"1120","1098":"1098","1174":"1174","1